    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-17615727">
      <hr />
      <div id="comment-17615727" class="comment-wrapper ">
        <div class="comment-author vcard">
          <div class="comment-avatar big-avatar">
                          <a href="/follow/people/4e53d5ab31829740fd000923/" data-badges="0" data-followers="0">            
                <img class='avatar avatar-50 photo' src='http://6.mshcdn.com/follow/uploads/user/avatar/61/54/77/84/68/8c/thumb_gunther-pott-86d5aef683.jpg' />              </a>
                      </div>

          <span class='author-link'><a href='/follow/people/4e53d5ab31829740fd000923/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Gunther Pott</a></span>
                                    <a href="/follow/people/4e53d5ab31829740fd000923/follow/" class="follow_button" data-badges="0" data-followers="0">Follow</a>
                                        </div>

        <div class="comment-body">
          <p>Disruptive? Maybe in a few years. EFB&#8217;s have been around for years, and with much more integration and capabilities than what those ipads will present us with for now. Airplanes like the 787 or the A380 have much better EFB&#8217;s built right into the airplane. This was just the cheapest mass produced pdf reader the airlines could get approved by the FAA.<br />
But don&#8217;t get me wrong:  it&#8217;s a great first step by the airline into this century and the really great part will come with the right apps and maybe some connection to the real-time world and then this ipad deal will open up great possibilities&#8230; just don&#8217;t expect eager funding from the FAA, and don&#8217;t expect better air traffic control for some time to come either.<br />
Oh yeah, United: maybe you should finally donate the old &#8216;Unimatic&#8217; to the computer museum and get a somewhat modern system. Yes, I know, after 40+ years, it is a really stable system and with all them&#8217; tubes in there, it keeps the building toasty without using the heater, but, c&#8217;mon&#8230;still typing 6-digit codes on the greenscreen &#8230; really?!</p>
                  </div>

